 areas in which new materials will transform our lives in the twenty-first century. The chapters provide vignettes from a broad range of selected areas of materials science and can be read as separate essays. The subjects include photonic materials, materials for information storage, smart materials, biomaterials, biomedical materials, materials for clean energy, porous materials, diamond and hard materials, new polymers, and surfaces and interfaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aSCIENCE / Chemistry / General.2bisacsh  aAerogel.  aAlkyl.  aAmino acid.  aAntiferromagnetism.  aArgon.  aAsperity (materials science).  aBacteria.  aBacteriorhodopsin.  aBand gap.  aBilayer.  aBioglass.  aBoron nitride.  aBoron.  aBranching (polymer chemistry).  aCarbon.  aCarrier generation and recombination.  aCatalysis.  aChain reaction.  aChemical bond.  aChemical industry.  aChemical vapor deposition.  aChemist.  aChromophore.  aCoercivity.  aCopolymer.  aCrystal structure.  aCrystal.  aDendrimer.  aDetergent.  aDiode.  aDopant.  aElectric charge.  aElectric field.  aElectrode.  aElectrolyte.  aElectrorheological fluid.  aEnzyme.  aExtrinsic semiconductor.  aHigh pressure.  aHydrocarbon.  aJohn Bardeen.  aLaser diode.  aLaser.  aLipid.  aLithium niobate.  aMagnetization.  aMartensite.  aMaterials science.  aMetglas.  aMicrometer.  aMixture.  aMolecular sieve.  aMolecule.  aMonomer.  aNoble metal.  aNonlinear optics.  aNylon.  aOptical fiber.  aPeptide.  aPhospholipid.  aPhoton.  aPiezoelectricity.  aPlastic.  aPolyacetylene.  aPolymer.  aPolymerization.  aPolytetrafluoroethylene.  aPopulation inversion.  aProcessing (Chinese materia medica).  aProtein.  aQuantum well.  aRadical (chemistry).  